Data-based Statistical Decision Model

Lecture 6 - Model checking and inference for multivariate linear models

Sungkyu Jung

Review: Multiple regression model

In the multiple linear regression model, we assume that the response Y is a linear function of all the predictors, plus a constant, plus noise: \[ Y = \beta_0 +_1X_1 +_2X_2 +\cdots + _pX_p + .\]

We make no assumptions about the (marginal or joint) distributions of the \(X_i\), but we assume that \(E [|X] = 0\), \(Var [|X] = ^2\), and that \(\) is uncorrelated across measurements.

In a matrix form, the model is \[ \mathbf{Y} = \mathbf{X} + . \]

When we add the Gaussian noise assumption, we are making all of the assumptions above, and further assuming that \[ N(0, \sigma^2 {\mathbf I}).\] independently of X.

  • Estimates of coefficients: \({\mathbf B}= \hat\beta = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}\).

  • Fitted values: \(\hat{{\mathbf Y}} = \hat{m}({\mathbf X}) = {\mathbf X}\hat\beta = {\mathbf X}({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}= {\mathbf H}{\mathbf Y}\).

  • Residuals: \({\mathbf e}= {\mathbf Y}- \hat{\mathbf Y}= ({\mathbf I}- {\mathbf H}) {\mathbf Y}\).

  • Point predictions: To predict the conditional mean of \(Y\) at a point \({\mathbf X}= {\mathbf x}_*\), \[\hat{m}({\mathbf x}_*) = {\mathbf x}_*' \hat\beta = {\mathbf x}_*'({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}.\]

Adding Curvature: Polynomial Regression

If the relationship between \(Y\) and \(X\) is non-linear, we could try to capture that fact with a polynomial. For example, we could use a model like \[Y =_0+_1X_1+_2X^2_1+_3X_2+.\]

This is just a multiple linear regression model with (now) THREE predictors: \[(X_1,X_1^2, X_2)\]

Lets see how this is done in R. Lets ignore lowtemp for now, and regress volume on hightemp.

  1. We can manually create hightemp2.
PData <- RailTrail %>% mutate(hightemp2 = hightemp * hightemp)
lm(volume ~ hightemp + hightemp2, data = PData)

What does poly(x, degree = 2) do?

  • Produces polynomials of x orthogonal to each other (in the data)

  • So that x and x^2 are linearly independent with each otherMore on this when we discuss collinearity.

xpoly <- poly(hightemp,2)
plot(hightemp, xpoly[,1])
plot(hightemp, xpoly[,2])

They are the same models, same fits, and produce the identical predictions.

  geom_point()

g + geom_smooth(method = 'lm', formula = y ~ poly(x,2))

What has gone wrong, again?

The problem is collinearity. See that there was no winter, thus

  • if you know the values of two variables, you know the other.

  • three variables are linearly dependent.

  • \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) is not invertible,

  • \(\hat\beta = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}\) not defined.

Why do we have NA?

Handling Qualitative variables (Categorical variables)

Binary variable (two categories)

If a variable \(X\) has two possible values Yes, No (or Male, Female, etc), we code the qualitative categories as 0 and 1. This variable is called a dummy variable.

\[Y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 X + \beta_2 Z + \epsilon,\]

where \(X\) is either 0 or 1 (and \(Z\) is another numeric predictor).

The coefficient \(_1\) is the expected difference in \(Y\) between two units which are identical, except that one of them has \(X = 0\) and the other has \(X = 1\). That is, its the expected difference in the response between members of the reference category and members of the other category, all else being equal. For this reason, \(_1\) is often called the contrast between the two classes.

Categorical variables with more than two categories

The Cherry Blossom 10 Mile Run is a road race held in Washington, D.C. in April each year. (The name comes from the famous cherry trees that are in bloom in April in Washington.) The results of this race are published. This data frame contains the results from the 2005 race.

glimpse(TenMileRace)

  • Variable state has US state names as values, i.e.it is a categorical variable with many categories.

  • The type of state variable is <fct>, i.e.a factor. This indicates that state variable is a categorical variable. Different values of a factor are called levels.

  • To code this variable, say with \(k\) categories, we pick one level it really doesnt matter which as the reference level. We then introduce \(k 1\) columns into the design matrix \({\mathbf X}\), which are indicators for the other categories.

For example, lets take VA as the reference level (and suppose there are only four categories shown above), then the (first three rows of) design matrix would be:

0 0 0
1 0 0
0 0 0

Ordinal variables

An ordinal variable is one where the qualitatively-distinct levels can be put in a sensible order, but theres no implication that the distance from one level to the next is constant. At our present level of sophistication, we have basically two ways to handle them:

  1. Ignoring the ordering and treat them like nominal categorical variables.
    • Unbiased
    • Could have many, so many, distinct coefficients
  2. Ignoring the fact that theyre only ordinal, assign them numerical codes (say 1, 2, 3, . . . ) and treat them like ordinary numerical variables.
    • Easy
    • Without any substantive or logical basis
    • It implies that each step up in the ordinal variable will predict exactly the same difference in \(Y\) , and why should that be the case?

Should we regard a categorical variable as ordinal or nomial?

Take a look at this big dataset, MosaicData::HELPfull.

Patients with no primary care physician were randomized to receive a multidisciplinary assessment and a brief motivational intervention or usual care, with the goal of linking them to primary medical care.

(https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/mosaicData/mosaicData.pdf)

Diagnostics and model checking

Recall models and few calculations:

  • Model:\(\mathbf{Y} = \mathbf{X} + .\)

  • With the Gaussian noise assumption $ N(0, ^2 )$ independently of X.

  • Estimates of coefficients: \({\mathbf B}= \hat\beta = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}\).

  • Fitted values: \(\hat{{\mathbf Y}} = \hat{m}({\mathbf X}) = {\mathbf X}\hat\beta = {\mathbf X}({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}= {\mathbf H}{\mathbf Y}\).

  • Residuals: \({\mathbf e}= {\mathbf Y}- \hat{\mathbf Y}= ({\mathbf I}- {\mathbf H}) {\mathbf Y}\).

More on residuals

  • In Sample MSE \(\hat\sigma^2 = \frac{1}{n} {\mathbf e}'{\mathbf e}\). Alternatively we can use \(s^2 = \frac{n}{n-p}\hat\sigma^2\).

  • Constant + Noise form of residuals: \[ {\mathbf e}= ({\mathbf I}- {\mathbf H}) {\mathbf Y}\\ = ({\mathbf I}- {\mathbf H}) ({\mathbf X}\beta + \epsilon) \\ = ({\mathbf I}- {\mathbf H})\epsilon \\ = \epsilon + {\mathbf H}\epsilon \]

  • Hence, \(E[{\mathbf e}]=0\) and \(Var[{\mathbf e}]=^2({\mathbf I}{\mathbf H})\).

  • Under the Gaussian noise assumption, \({\mathbf e}\) is Gaussian as well.

  • (\({\mathbf e}\) and \({\mathbf X}\)) and (\({\mathbf e}\) and \(\hat{y}\)) should also be uncorrelated.

Basic model checking

All of the plots we learned how to do for simple linear regression remain valuable:

  1. Plot the residuals against the predictors. (This now means \(p\) distinct plots, of course.)

  2. Plot the squared residuals against the predictors. Each of these \(p\) plots should show a flat scatter of points around \(\sigma^2 \approx \hat\sigma^2\) or \(s^2\).

  3. Plot the residuals against the fitted values.

  4. Plot the squared residuals against the fitted values.

  5. Plot the residuals against coordinates.

  6. Plot the residuals distribution against a Gaussian (QQ plot)

  7. Out-of-sample predictions, with either random or deliberately selected testing sets, also remain valuable.

Collinearity

Why Collinearity Is a Problem

  • Estimates of coefficients: \({\mathbf B}= \hat\beta = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1} {\mathbf X}' {\mathbf Y}\).

  • This is obviously going to lead to problems if \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) isnt invertible.

  • Similarly, the variance of the estimates, \(Var(\hat\beta) = \sigma^2 ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1}\) will blow up when \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) is singular.

  • If that matrix isnt exactly singular, but is close to being non-invertible, the variances will become huge.

Collinearity can happen

  • Recall from last lecture slides, if there are more predictor variables than the number of observations, i.e., \(n < p\), \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) is NOT invertible.

  • By poor coding. Recall RailTrail example.

  • Again, if there isnt an exact linear relationship among the predictors, but theyre close to one, \(({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1}\) will be huge, and the variances of the estimated coefficients will be enormous. This can make it very hard to say anything at all precise about the coefficients

Detecing collinearity

  1. Diagnosing Collinearity Among Pairs of Variables

  2. Variance Inflation Factors

Multicollinearity is sometimes hard to detect

Recall hightemp + lowtemp = 2 avgtemp (A perfect set of multicollinear variables). By looking at the pairs of variables, we have:

library(car)
scatterplotMatrix(~ hightemp + lowtemp + avgtemp, data = RailTrail)

3D scatterplot can help, because there are only three variables.

scatter3d(avgtemp ~ hightemp + lowtemp, data = RailTrail, surface = FALSE)

What can you do when there are more than 3 variables?

Eigendecomposition

  • Note that \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) is a square matrix and (roughly) the sample variance-covariance matrix of \({\mathbf X}\).

  • If \({\mathbf X}\) follows multivariate Normal distribution, then the sample variance-covariance matrix of \({\mathbf X}\) gives a contour of density function, which is always an ellipse (or ellipsoid).

  • Eigendecomposition provides
    • the direction of major axis
    • the (squared) length of the axis
  • Thus, \(eigenvalue = 0\) means that the distribution is degenerate (i.e.there is a perfect linear relationship among variable)
  • Small eigenvalue of \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) (or the sample variance of \({\mathbf X}\)) is a sign of nearly multicollinear variables.
eigen(var(select(RailTrail, spring:fall)))$values
## [1] 3.952626e-01 1.692818e-01 5.551115e-17

VIF

If the predictors are correlated with each other, the standard errors of the coefficient estimates will be bigger than if the predictors were uncorrelated.

  • If the predictors were uncorrelated, i.e. \({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}\) is a diagonal matrix, then

\[Var(\hat\beta_i) = \frac{\sigma^2}{ns_{X_i}^2}\]

just as in the simple regression.

  • With correlated predictors, \[Var(\hat\beta_i) = \sigma^2 ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1}_{(i+1,i+1)}.\]

  • The variance inflation factor for the ith coefficient is \[ VIF_i = \frac{({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X})^{-1}_{(i+1,i+1)}}{ns_{X_i}^2}.\]

  • Folklore says that \(VIF_i > 10\) indicates serious multicollinearity for the predictor.

An R example

# glimpse(MASS::Boston)
# lm.col <- lm(medv ~ ., data = MASS::Boston)
# vif(lm.col)
lm.col2 <- MASS::Boston %>% mutate(duh = crim + zn + rnorm(nrow(.))) %>% lm(medv ~ ., data = .)
vif(lm.col2)
##       crim         zn      indus       chas        nox         rm 
##  84.350670 606.093682   3.991744   1.074237   4.396303   1.936160 
##        age        dis        rad        tax    ptratio      black 
##   3.105206   3.970484   7.494236   9.013613   1.799567   1.348525 
##      lstat        duh 
##   2.942014 599.474012

Remedies for multicollinearity

The real problem with collinearity is that when it happens, there isnt a unique solution to the estimating equations. We can choose to do:

  1. Dropping predictor variables

  2. Ridge regression

There are indeed hundreds of remedies for collinearity, as all high-dimensional regression problems are collinear. This is an active area of research since early 2000. We will see some options throughout the course.

Ridge regression

Recall that in the ordinary least squares, we minimize

\[MSE(\beta) = \frac{1}{n}({\mathbf Y}- {\mathbf X}\beta)' ({\mathbf Y}- {\mathbf X}\beta).\]

Instead, minimize

\[R(\beta) = \frac{1}{n}({\mathbf Y}- {\mathbf X}\beta)' ({\mathbf Y}- {\mathbf X}\beta) + \frac{\lambda}{n}{\left\Vert\beta\right\Vert}^2.\]

For a penalty factor \(\lambda >0\). The penalty factor, or tuning parameter \( > 0\) will lead to a solution with some bias but it reduces the variance. In particular, it solves the problem of non-invertibility.

  • The solution to the ridge regression is

\[\hat\beta_\lambda = ({\mathbf X}'{\mathbf X}+ \lambda {\mathbf I})^{-1}{\mathbf X}'{\mathbf Y}.\]

  • This is biased, but can have smaller variance than the ordinary least-squares solution.

  • We usually choose \(\lambda\) using cross-validation which we will explain later in the course.

Other penalties

  • If you choose to minimize

\[R(\beta) = \frac{1}{n}({\mathbf Y}- {\mathbf X}\beta)' ({\mathbf Y}- {\mathbf X}\beta) + \frac{\lambda}{n}\sum_{j=1}^p |\beta_j|,\]

its called LASSO regression.

Outliers and influential points

  • An outlier is a point with a large residual.

  • An influential point is a point that has a large impact on the regression.

Leverage

  • Recall \(\hat{{\mathbf Y}} = {\mathbf H}{\mathbf Y}\). This means that each \(Y_i\) is a linear combination of elements of \({\mathbf H}\). In particular, \(h_{ii} = H_{ii}\) is the contribution of the \(i\)th data point to the prediction of \(Y_i\). For this reason we call \(h_{ii}\) the leverage.

  • If you looked at residual plots, you would see problems in the second and third case. But the resdual plot for the fourth example would look fine.

  • You cant see influence in the usual residual plot.

Modified residual

Standardized residual

Recall that

\[{\mathbf e}=({\mathbf I}{\mathbf H}), \quad E[{\mathbf e}]={\mathbf 0}, Var({\mathbf e})=^2({\mathbf I}{\mathbf H}).\]

The standard error of \(e_i\) is \(\hat\sigma (1 - h_ii).\)

  • The standardized residual for \(i\)th observation is then \[r_i = \frac{r_i}{\hat\sigma (1 - h_ii)}.\]

Cross-validated residual

  • To see how the fit would be different if the \(i\)th observation wasnt there, we consider fitting a linear regression without the \(i\)th observation, then compare it to the full regression fit.

  • Fit a linear regression line with all observation except \((y_i, {\mathbf x}_i)\), then predict the conditional mean of \(y_i\) at \({\mathbf X}= {\mathbf x}_i\); Call the predicted value \[\hat{Y}_{i(i)},\] and the collection of those in a vector form by \({\mathbf Y}^{(-1)}\).

  • the jackknife residual, the cross-validated residual, externally studentized residual or studentized deleted residual is \[t_i = \frac{Y_i - \hat{Y}_{i(i)}}{s_i},\] where \(s_i\) is the estimated standard error of \(y_i - \hat{Y}_{i(i)}\).

Cookss distance

  • How much do the fitted values change if we omit an observation?

  • Cooks distance \(D_i\) measures a standardized change for each observation:

\[D_i = \frac{({\mathbf Y} {\mathbf Y}^{(-1)})'({\mathbf Y} {\mathbf Y}^{(-1)})}{(p+1)\hat\sigma^2}.\]

  • With some algebra, \[D_i = \left(\frac{r_i^2}{p+1}\right)\left(\frac{h_{ii}{1-h_{ii}\right).\]

  • Cooks distance is large (or influence is large) if either (or both)

  1. studentized residual \(r_i\) is large in magnitude or/and
  2. the leverage \(h_ii\) is large.
  • Often, people interpret \(D_i > 1\) as an influential point.

Diagnostics in Practice

We have three ways of looking at whether points are outliers (or influential):

  1. Leverage \(h_{ii}\)

  2. Studentized residuals, either ordinary or cross-validated (\(r_i\) or \(t_i\))

  3. Cooks distance.

Example

Lets return to the Chicago data. There were indeed more numeric variables, so we use some of them to form a multiple linear regression model. Everything we talked can be computed as follows:

library(gamair)
data(chicago)
out<-lm(death ~ tmpd + o3median + so2median +  pm10median, data = chicago)
# hatvalues(out) 
# influence(out)$hat  ### this is the same as the previous line
# rstandard(out)      ### standardized residuals
# rstudent(out)       ### jackknife residuals
# cooks.distance(out) ### Cook's distance

We can plot them:

n = nrow(chicago) 
plot(hatvalues(out),ylab="Leverage")
plot(rstandard(out),ylab="Standardized Residuals")
plot(rstudent(out),ylab="Cross-Validated Residuals")
abline(h=qt(0.025,df=n-2),col="red")
abline(h=qt(1-0.025,df=n-2),col="red")
plot(cooks.distance(out),ylab="Cook's Distance")

We can also inspect which data points produced the largest residuals or Cooks distance:

r = rstudent(out)
I = (1:n)[rank(-abs(r)) <= 3] ## indices 3 largest residuals

plot(out)

  1. Residuals versus fitted values, plus a smoothing line, with extreme residuals marked by row number.

  2. A Q-Q plot of the standardized residuals, again with extremes marked by row number.

  3. The square root of the absolute standardized residuals against fitted values (ideally, flat).

  4. Standardized residuals against leverage, with contour lines showing equal values of Cooks distance.
